A Dynamical Systems Theory of Aging: Mathematical Foundations, Stability Analysis, and Control Strategies

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

Aging is conceptualized as the loss of stability in a coupled biological system. This thesis develops a rigorous mathematical framework modeling aging through nonlinear ordinary differential equations that describe interactions between cellular energy (ATP), mitochondrial function, telomere length, epigenetic information, NAD⁺ availability, and cellular senescence burden. Using bifurcation theory, we prove that parameter drift (aging) leads from a stable equilibrium (youth) to instability via a Hopf bifurcation under explicit conditions derived via the Routh–Hurwitz criterion. The analysis yields testable predictions of critical slowing down, including increased variance and autocorrelation of biomarker fluctuations prior to health decline. Stochastic extensions formalize these early‑warning signals. Optimal control theory provides existence and characterization of interventions to restore stability, with a proof that combined interventions (e.g., NAD⁺ supplementation plus senolytics) can recover stability after the bifurcation threshold, whereas single interventions may fail. Numerical simulations (proposed) illustrate the theoretical results. This work establishes a mathematically grounded foundation for aging as a controllable dynamical system, culminating in Ouadi’s Theorem on Aging as Dynamical Instability.

---

Chapter 1: Introduction and Literature Review

1.1 The Unifying Problem of Aging

Aging is a universal, progressive decline in physiological function that increases susceptibility to disease and death. Despite decades of research, no single theory explains why aging occurs or how it might be reversed. The identification of twelve interconnected hallmarks of aging—genomic instability, telomere attrition, epigenetic alterations, loss of proteostasis, disabled macroautophagy, deregulated nutrient‑sensing, mitochondrial dysfunction, cellular senescence, stem cell exhaustion, altered intercellular communication, chronic inflammation, and dysbiosis (López-Otín et al., 2023)—has revealed a complex network of interacting processes. These hallmarks are not independent; they engage in positive and negative feedback loops that amplify damage over time.

Yet a unifying mathematical framework that integrates these processes into a predictive, testable model remains absent. Most existing quantitative models focus on mortality curves (e.g., the Gompertz law) or on individual molecular pathways. A growing body of work distinguishes between network maps (static topologies) and dynamical models (temporal evolution) as two pillars of computational aging research (Johnson et al., 2025). The former help identify molecular hubs; the latter aim to predict trajectories and responses to interventions.

This thesis posits that aging can be understood as the loss of stability in a nonlinear dynamical system coupling key variables: energy metabolism (ATP), mitochondrial integrity, telomere length, epigenetic fidelity, NAD⁺ availability, and cellular senescence burden. By applying tools from dynamical systems theory, bifurcation analysis, stochastic processes, and optimal control, we derive testable predictions and propose rational intervention strategies.

1.2 Literature Review

1.2.1 The Hallmarks Framework and Its Mathematical Interpretations

The hallmarks of aging (López-Otín et al., 2023) provide a conceptual map. Cellular senescence has emerged as a central driver of age‑related pathology, primarily through the Senescence‑Associated Secretory Phenotype (SASP)—a pro‑inflammatory secretome that spreads damage to neighboring cells (Gorgoulis et al., 2019). Senescent cells accumulate with age, and their removal via senolytic drugs extends healthspan in animal models and shows promise in early human trials (Kirkland & Tchkonia, 2020). This makes senescence a natural control node.

Mathematically, the hallmarks have been represented in network models that identify feedback loops (e.g., mTOR‑autophagy, NAD⁺‑sirtuin axes). However, static networks do not capture the temporal dynamics that lead to catastrophic failure.

1.2.2 Dynamical Systems Models of Aging

Minimal dynamical models have captured universal patterns of mortality and frailty. Beltrán‑Sánchez and colleagues (2025) proposed a three‑variable model (damage, repair, and a resilience factor) that reproduces the observed acceleration of mortality with age. These models show that aging can be interpreted as a bifurcation: a qualitative change in system behavior when a parameter (e.g., repair capacity) crosses a threshold.

More detailed ODE models have been developed for specific subsystems, such as mitochondrial – NAD⁺ – ROS interactions, but they rarely integrate multiple hallmarks. A recent review (Johnson et al., 2025) emphasizes the need for multi‑variable models that are both mechanistic and analytically tractable.

1.2.3 Critical Slowing Down and Early Warnings

The concept of critical slowing down (Scheffer et al., 2018) has been applied to biological systems ranging from ecosystems to human physiology. As a system approaches a bifurcation, its recovery rate from perturbations decreases, leading to increased variance and autocorrelation in time series. In aging, this has been observed in physiological markers such as heart rate variability and gait speed before major health declines. A 2025 analysis of the Frailty Index in a large cohort identified a tipping point around age 75 where resilience collapses (Dalhousie University, 2025), aligning with the bifurcation perspective.

1.2.4 Control‑Theoretic Approaches to Biological Stabilization

Optimal control theory has been applied to metabolic networks, drug dosing, and cancer therapy, but only recently to aging. The Biomarkers of Aging Challenge (2024–2025) has accelerated the development of robust measures of biological age (Bucaciuc et al., 2025), making it possible to design feedback controllers that maintain these measures near a youthful setpoint. Senolytics and NAD⁺ precursors (e.g., NMN, NR) are currently being tested in clinical trials, providing a real‑world testbed for multi‑intervention strategies.

1.3 Thesis Contributions and Outline

This thesis makes the following contributions:

1. A minimal ODE model capturing six core aging variables (ATP, mitochondrial function, telomere length, epigenetic fidelity, NAD⁺, and cellular senescence) with biologically motivated coupling.
2. A rigorous stability analysis showing that the youth equilibrium is locally asymptotically stable under nominal parameters.
3. A derivation of explicit conditions on the senescence clearance rate under which a Hopf bifurcation occurs, using the Routh–Hurwitz criterion for a 6th‑order system. This derivation forms the basis of Ouadi’s Theorem.
4. A stochastic extension that yields testable early‑warning signals (variance and autocorrelation increase), linked to specific biomarkers via a measurement model.
5. A control‑theoretic framework for intervention, including an optimal control formulation and a post‑bifurcation synergy theorem showing that combined interventions (NAD⁺ supplementation plus senolytics) can restore stability when single interventions cannot.
6. Numerical simulation proposals to illustrate the theoretical results; the simulations will be executed using the parameter values provided in Appendix B.

The thesis is organized as follows. Chapter 2 presents mathematical preliminaries. Chapter 3 introduces the model with six state variables. Chapter 4 performs stability analysis, derives Hopf conditions, and states Ouadi’s Theorem. Chapter 5 adds stochasticity, defines early‑warning signals, and provides a measurement model. Chapter 6 develops control strategies, focusing on post‑bifurcation recovery. Chapter 7 outlines numerical validation plans. Chapter 8 discusses limitations and future directions. Chapter 9 concludes.

Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries

This chapter provides the mathematical foundations necessary for the development of the thesis. We cover the theory of ordinary differential equations (ODEs), linearization and stability, bifurcation theory (with emphasis on Hopf bifurcations), stochastic differential equations (SDEs), and elements of control theory. All definitions, theorems, and proofs are presented in a self‑contained manner, with references to standard texts for detailed derivations.

---

2.1 Dynamical Systems and Ordinary Differential Equations

2.1.1 Basic Definitions

Let  \mathbb{R}^n  denote the n-dimensional Euclidean space and \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}^n the non‑negative orthant. Consider a system of ordinary differential equations

\frac{dx}{dt} = f(x; p), \qquad x(0) = x_0 \in \mathbb{R}^n,
\tag{2.1}

where x(t) \in \mathbb{R}^n is the state vector, p \in \mathbb{R}^m is a parameter vector, and f : \mathbb{R}^n \times \mathbb{R}^m \to \mathbb{R}^n is a given function. We assume that f is continuously differentiable with respect to x and continuous in p. This ensures the existence and uniqueness of solutions for any initial condition x_0 and any finite time interval (Picard–Lindelöf theorem).

Definition 2.1 (Equilibrium). A point x^* \in \mathbb{R}^n is an equilibrium (or fixed point) of (2.1) if f(x^*; p) = 0.

An equilibrium represents a steady state of the system.

Definition 2.2 (Solution and Flow). For a fixed p, the solution of (2.1) with initial condition x_0 is denoted \phi(t; x_0). The family of maps \phi_t : x_0 \mapsto \phi(t; x_0) is called the flow of the system.

2.1.2 Linearization

Let x^* be an equilibrium. For small perturbations \xi = x - x^*, we expand f in a Taylor series around x^*:

f(x^* + \xi; p) = f(x^*; p) + \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}(x^*; p) \, \xi + O(\|\xi\|^2).

Since f(x^*; p)=0, the linear approximation is

\frac{d\xi}{dt} = J(p) \, \xi,
\tag{2.2}

where

J(p) = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}(x^*; p) \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n}

is the Jacobian matrix evaluated at the equilibrium.

Theorem 2.1 (Hartman–Grobman). If the Jacobian J has no eigenvalues with zero real part, then the nonlinear system (2.1) is topologically conjugate to its linearization (2.2) in a neighborhood of x^*. In particular, the stability of x^* is determined by the eigenvalues of J.

2.1.3 Stability Concepts

Definition 2.3 (Lyapunov Stability). An equilibrium x^* is Lyapunov stable if for every \varepsilon > 0 there exists \delta > 0 such that if \|x_0 - x^*\| < \delta, then \|\phi(t; x_0) - x^*\| < \varepsilon for all t \ge 0.

Definition 2.4 (Asymptotic Stability). x^* is asymptotically stable if it is Lyapunov stable and there exists \delta > 0 such that whenever \|x_0 - x^*\| < \delta, we have \lim_{t\to\infty} \phi(t; x_0) = x^*.

Definition 2.5 (Exponential Stability). x^* is exponentially stable if there exist constants \alpha > 0 and C > 0 such that for all t \ge 0 and all x_0 in a neighborhood, \|\phi(t; x_0) - x^*\| \le C e^{-\alpha t} \|x_0 - x^*\|.

Theorem 2.2 (Linearization Principle). If all eigenvalues of J have negative real parts, then the equilibrium x^* is exponentially stable (and thus asymptotically stable). If at least one eigenvalue has positive real part, then x^* is unstable.

Proof. See, e.g., Khalil (2002), Theorem 4.7. ∎

---

2.2 Bifurcation Theory

2.2.1 Parameter Dependence

Let the system depend on a scalar parameter \lambda \in \mathbb{R} (e.g., a biological parameter that changes with age). We write

\frac{dx}{dt} = f(x; \lambda).

As \lambda varies, the equilibrium x^*(\lambda) and its stability may change.

Definition 2.6 (Bifurcation Point). A parameter value \lambda_0 is a bifurcation point if the topological structure of the flow changes at \lambda_0.

Definition 2.7 (Hopf Bifurcation). A Hopf bifurcation occurs when a pair of complex conjugate eigenvalues of J(\lambda) crosses the imaginary axis with non‑zero speed, giving rise to a limit cycle.

Formally, assume that for \lambda < \lambda_0 the eigenvalues \alpha(\lambda) \pm i \beta(\lambda) have \alpha(\lambda) < 0, at \lambda = \lambda_0 we have \alpha(\lambda_0) = 0, \beta(\lambda_0) = \omega \neq 0, and d\alpha/d\lambda \big|_{\lambda_0} \neq 0. Moreover, all other eigenvalues have negative real parts at \lambda_0.

Theorem 2.3 (Hopf Bifurcation Theorem). Under the above conditions, there exists a family of periodic orbits bifurcating from the equilibrium at \lambda = \lambda_0. The period of the orbits is close to 2\pi/\omega. The bifurcation is supercritical if the stable periodic orbit exists for \lambda > \lambda_0 (when the equilibrium is unstable) and subcritical if it exists for \lambda < \lambda_0 (when the equilibrium is still stable). The direction and stability of the bifurcation are determined by the sign of the first Lyapunov coefficient.

Proof. See Guckenheimer & Holmes (1983), Chapter 3. ∎

2.2.2 Routh–Hurwitz Criterion

For a polynomial

P(\sigma) = a_0 \sigma^n + a_1 \sigma^{n-1} + \dots + a_n, \quad a_0 > 0,

the Routh–Hurwitz criterion provides necessary and sufficient conditions for all roots to have negative real parts. The criterion is based on the Hurwitz determinants:

\Delta_1 = a_1, \quad
\Delta_2 = \begin{vmatrix} a_1 & a_0 \\ a_3 & a_2 \end{vmatrix}, \quad
\Delta_3 = \begin{vmatrix} a_1 & a_0 & 0 \\ a_3 & a_2 & a_1 \\ a_5 & a_4 & a_3 \end{vmatrix}, \quad \dots

All roots have negative real parts iff \Delta_i > 0 for all i = 1, \dots, n. For a Hopf bifurcation to occur in an n-dimensional system, one needs \Delta_i > 0 for all i < n and \Delta_n = 0, with the additional transversality condition (Liu, 1994).

