2.3 Stochastic Differential Equations

2.3.1 Itô Calculus

To account for intrinsic fluctuations, we consider stochastic differential equations of the form

dx = f(x; p) \, dt + g(x) \, dW_t, \qquad x(0) = x_0,
\tag{2.3}

where W_t is an m-dimensional Wiener process (Brownian motion) with independent components, and g(x) \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times m} is the diffusion matrix. The equation is interpreted in the Itô sense.

Definition 2.8 (Wiener Process). A stochastic process W_t is a Wiener process if:

· W_0 = 0 almost surely.
· It has independent increments.
· W_t - W_s \sim \mathcal{N}(0, (t-s)I) for t > s.
· Its paths are continuous almost surely.

Theorem 2.4 (Existence and Uniqueness). If f and g are globally Lipschitz, then (2.3) has a unique strong solution for any initial condition.

2.3.2 Linear Stochastic Systems and the Lyapunov Equation

Consider a linear SDE

d\xi = J \xi \, dt + \sigma \, dW_t,
\tag{2.4}

where J \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n} is Hurwitz (all eigenvalues have negative real parts) and \sigma \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times m} is constant. The stationary covariance \Sigma = \mathbb{E}[\xi \xi^\top] satisfies the Lyapunov equation:

J \Sigma + \Sigma J^\top + \sigma \sigma^\top = 0.
\tag{2.5}

Theorem 2.5 (Solution of Lyapunov Equation). If J is Hurwitz, then (2.5) has a unique symmetric positive semi‑definite solution given by

\Sigma = \int_0^\infty e^{J t} \sigma \sigma^\top e^{J^\top t} \, dt.

Proof. See, e.g., Arnold (1974), Chapter 8. ∎

As the real part of the dominant eigenvalue approaches zero, the integral diverges, leading to unbounded variance—a signature of critical slowing down.

