2.4 Control Theory

2.4.1 Controllability

Consider a linear time‑invariant system

\dot{x} = A x + B u, \qquad x \in \mathbb{R}^n, \quad u \in \mathbb{R}^m,
\tag{2.6}

with A \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n}, B \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times m}.

Definition 2.9 (Controllability). The pair (A,B) is controllable if for any initial state x_0 and any final state x_f, there exists an input u(t) that steers the system from x_0 to x_f in finite time.

Theorem 2.6 (Kalman Controllability Criterion). (A,B) is controllable iff the controllability matrix

\mathcal{C} = [B, AB, A^2 B, \dots, A^{n-1}B]

has full row rank (i.e., rank \mathcal{C} = n).

Theorem 2.7 (Popov–Belevitch–Hautus (PBH) Test). (A,B) is controllable iff for every eigenvalue \lambda of A, the matrix [\lambda I - A, \; B] has full row rank.

Proof. See, e.g., Kailath (1980). ∎

2.4.2 State Feedback and Pole Placement

We consider state feedback u = -K x, yielding the closed‑loop dynamics \dot{x} = (A - B K) x.

Theorem 2.8 (Pole Placement). If (A,B) is controllable, then for any desired set of eigenvalues \{\mu_1, \dots, \mu_n\} that is closed under complex conjugation, there exists a feedback gain K such that the eigenvalues of A - B K are exactly \{\mu_i\}.

Proof. This is a standard result in linear control theory; see, e.g., Kailath (1980), Chapter 3. ∎

2.4.3 Optimal Control

Consider the optimal control problem

\begin{aligned}
\text{minimize} \quad & J(u) = \int_0^T \big( (x-x^*)^{\top} Q (x-x^*) + u^{\top} R u \big) dt + (x(T)-x^*)^{\top} P (x(T)-x^*), \\
\text{subject to} \quad & \dot{x} = f(x) + B u, \quad x(0)=x_0, \quad u(t) \in \mathcal{U},
\end{aligned}
\tag{2.7}

where Q \succeq 0, R \succ 0, P \succeq 0, and \mathcal{U} \subset \mathbb{R}^m is a closed convex set.

Theorem 2.9 (Pontryagin’s Maximum Principle). Let u^* be an optimal control and x^* the corresponding state trajectory. Then there exists a costate function \lambda(t) such that the Hamiltonian

H(x, \lambda, u) = (x-x^*)^{\top} Q (x-x^*) + u^{\top} R u + \lambda^{\top} (f(x) + B u)

satisfies:

1. State equation: \dot{x} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial \lambda}\big|_{x^*, \lambda, u^*}.
2. Costate equation: \dot{\lambda} = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial x}\big|_{x^*, \lambda, u^*}.
3. Boundary condition: \lambda(T) = 2P (x(T)-x^*).
4. Optimality condition: u^* minimizes H over \mathcal{U} at each time.

Proof. See, e.g., Fleming & Rishel (1975). ∎

For quadratic cost and linear dynamics, the optimal control can be expressed as a linear feedback: u^*(t) = -R^{-1} B^{\top} S(t) x(t), where S(t) solves the Riccati differential equation.

