Chapter 6: Control Theory and Intervention Strategies

In this chapter, we develop a control‑theoretic approach to stabilizing the aging system. We formulate an optimal control problem for interventions such as NAD⁺ supplementation and senolytic drugs, prove existence of optimal controls, and derive necessary conditions. We then address feedback stabilization, focusing on the post‑bifurcation regime where single interventions may fail but combined interventions succeed. We introduce a distinction between senolytics (which clear senescent cells) and senomorphics (which suppress the SASP) and show how they can be integrated into the control framework.

---

6.1 Control‑Affine System

We consider the system (3.1)–(3.6) with control inputs affecting specific variables. The control vector is

u(t) = \begin{pmatrix} u_1(t) \\ u_2(t) \\ u_3(t) \end{pmatrix},

where:

· u_1(t) \in [0,1] represents NAD⁺ precursor supplementation (e.g., NMN, NR), acting directly on the N equation.
· u_2(t) \in [0,1] represents senolytic treatment (e.g., dasatinib+quercetin, ABT‑263), which increases the clearance rate of senescent cells.
· u_3(t) \in [0,1] represents senomorphic treatment (e.g., JAK inhibitors), which suppresses the SASP, i.e., reduces the coupling coefficients \phi_S, \lambda_S, \delta_S, \psi_S.

The controlled dynamics become:

\begin{aligned}
\frac{dN}{dt} &= -\alpha N + \beta_1 u_1 + S_N - \psi D - \psi_S S, \tag{6.1} \\
\frac{dS}{dt} &= \kappa (1-S) \left( \frac{R}{K_R+R} + \frac{D}{K_D+D} + \frac{1-I}{K_I+1-I} \right) - (\theta + \beta_2 u_2) S, \tag{6.2} \\
\frac{dM}{dt} &= -a M + b \frac{N}{K_N+N} - \phi R - (\phi_S - \beta_3 u_3) S, \tag{6.3} \\
\frac{dL}{dt} &= -\lambda L + \mu \frac{N}{K_N+N} - (\lambda_S - \beta_3' u_3) S, \tag{6.4} \\
\frac{dI}{dt} &= \gamma E + \gamma_N \frac{N}{K_N+N} - \delta I - (\delta_S - \beta_3'' u_3) S, \tag{6.5} \\
\frac{dE}{dt} &= k_1 M - d_E E. \tag{6.6}
\end{aligned}

Here, \beta_1 is the efficacy of NAD⁺ supplementation, \beta_2 the efficacy of the senolytic, and \beta_3, \beta_3', \beta_3'' capture the reduction of SASP‑mediated damage by senomorphics. For simplicity, we can combine the senomorphic effect into a single reduction factor \beta_3 acting on all coupling coefficients, but the distinct coefficients can be kept for generality.

The system is written in control‑affine form:

\dot{x} = f(x) + B_1 u_1 + B_2 u_2 + B_3 u_3,
\tag{6.7}

with appropriate vectors B_1, B_2, B_3. The controls are bounded: u_i(t) \in [0,1].

---

6.2 Optimal Control Problem

We aim to keep the state near the youth equilibrium x^* while minimizing control effort. The cost functional is quadratic:

J(u) = \int_0^T \big( (x(t)-x^*)^{\top} Q (x(t)-x^*) + u(t)^{\top} R u(t) \big) dt + (x(T)-x^*)^{\top} P (x(T)-x^*),
\tag{6.8}

where Q \succeq 0 penalizes deviations from the target, R \succ 0 penalizes control effort, and P \succeq 0 is a terminal cost.

Theorem 6.1 (Existence of Optimal Control). For any finite horizon T>0, there exists an optimal control u^* \in L^2([0,T]; \mathbb{R}^3) with u_i(t) \in [0,1] that minimizes J(u) subject to (6.7).

Proof. The system is linear in controls, the control set is compact and convex, the cost is convex and coercive, and the dynamics are Lipschitz. By the Filippov–Cesari theorem (see, e.g., Fleming & Rishel, 1975), an optimal solution exists. ∎

---

6.3 Pontryagin’s Maximum Principle

Let \lambda(t) \in \mathbb{R}^6 be the costate vector. The Hamiltonian is

H(x, \lambda, u) = (x-x^*)^{\top} Q (x-x^*) + u^{\top} R u + \lambda^{\top} \big( f(x) + B_1 u_1 + B_2 u_2 + B_3 u_3 \big).
\tag{6.9}

The necessary conditions for optimality are:

· State equation: \dot{x} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial \lambda} = f(x) + B_1 u_1 + B_2 u_2 + B_3 u_3.
· Costate equation: \dot{\lambda} = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial x} = -2Q(x-x^*) - \left( \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}(x) \right)^{\top} \lambda.
· Boundary condition: \lambda(T) = 2P (x(T)-x^*).
· Optimality condition: For each t, u(t) minimizes H over [0,1]^3.

Since the Hamiltonian is separable in the controls and quadratic, the optimal control is a projection of the linear feedback term:

u_i^*(t) = \operatorname{Proj}_{[0,1]} \left( -\frac{1}{2R_{ii}} B_i^{\top} \lambda(t) \right), \quad i=1,2,3.
\tag{6.10}

This is a two‑point boundary value problem that can be solved numerically (e.g., by shooting or collocation).

---

6.4 Feedback Stabilization and Controllability

For long‑term intervention, we consider state‑feedback control: u = K (x - x^*). The closed‑loop linearization is

\dot{\xi} = (J + B K) \xi,
\tag{6.11}

where J is the Jacobian at x^*, and B = [B_1 \; B_2 \; B_3]. The goal is to choose K such that J+BK is Hurwitz.

Proposition 6.2 (Controllability). For the nominal parameters and the full control set (NAD⁺, senolytic, senomorphic), the pair (J,B) is controllable. In particular, the modes that become unstable as \theta decreases are reachable by the combined controls.

Proof. We can verify controllability using the PBH test: for any eigenvalue \lambda of J, the matrix [\lambda I - J, \; B] has full row rank. For the unstable modes (complex eigenvalues crossing the imaginary axis), the rank condition holds because the senolytic and senomorphic controls directly affect the equations for S and the damage coupling terms. A numerical check with the parameters in Appendix B confirms controllability. ∎

Theorem 6.3 (Feedback Stabilization). If (J,B) is controllable, then there exists a feedback gain K such that all eigenvalues of J+BK have negative real parts. Thus the equilibrium can be locally stabilized by state feedback.

Proof. Standard pole placement theorem (Kailath, 1980). ∎

---

6.5 Post‑Bifurcation Synergy: Combined Interventions

A more interesting scenario is when the system has already crossed the bifurcation threshold (\theta < \theta_c) so that the equilibrium is unstable. We ask whether a combination of interventions can restore stability even when each intervention alone cannot.

Definition 6.1 (Stabilizability). A control set \mathcal{U} (a subset of controls) is said to stabilize the system at x^* if there exists a feedback law u(t) \in \mathcal{U} such that the closed‑loop linearization is Hurwitz.

Theorem 6.4 (Post‑Bifurcation Synergy). Suppose that for \theta < \theta_c, the single controls u_1 (NAD⁺) and u_2 (senolytic) individually cannot stabilize the equilibrium (i.e., the pairs (J, B_1) and (J, B_2) are not stabilizable, or the necessary condition for eigenvalue placement fails). Assume, however, that the combined control set (B_1, B_2, B_3) is controllable and that the unstable eigenvalues are reachable by the combined inputs. Then there exist gains K such that the closed‑loop system with u = K (x-x^*) is Hurwitz.

Proof. By the PBH test, a mode associated with eigenvalue \lambda is uncontrollable by a given control matrix B if and only if there exists a left eigenvector v such that v^\top B = 0. For the single controls, suppose that the unstable eigenvalues \lambda_u have left eigenvectors v with v^\top B_1 = 0 and v^\top B_2 = 0 individually, but v^\top [B_1, B_2, B_3] \neq 0 (i.e., the combined matrix has non‑zero projection). Then the unstable mode is reachable by the combined control. By controllability of the combined system, we can assign all eigenvalues arbitrarily, in particular to the left half‑plane. ∎

Corollary 6.5 (Synergy of Senolytic and Senomorphic). Even if a senolytic alone fails to stabilize the system (e.g., because the unstable mode is not directly in the S equation), adding a senomorphic that reduces the coupling coefficients may render the mode controllable, leading to successful stabilization.

This result formalizes the intuition that multi‑target interventions can overcome the limitations of single‑target strategies, a concept that is clinically relevant for aging.

---

