Appendix D: Routh–Hurwitz Derivation for the 6‑Variable Model

The characteristic polynomial of the Jacobian J is

P(\sigma) = \sigma^6 + a_5 \sigma^5 + a_4 \sigma^4 + a_3 \sigma^3 + a_2 \sigma^2 + a_1 \sigma + a_0.

The coefficients a_i are functions of the parameters. Using the Routh–Hurwitz criterion, all roots have negative real parts iff the Hurwitz determinants \Delta_i > 0 for i=1,\dots,6. For a Hopf bifurcation, we require \Delta_1, \dots, \Delta_5 > 0 and \Delta_6 = 0 (since \Delta_6 = a_0 \Delta_5). The condition \Delta_5 = 0 gives an algebraic equation in the parameters. For our system, with \theta as the bifurcation parameter, this equation can be solved to obtain \theta_c. The explicit expression is:

\Delta_5 = \theta^2 \left( \text{positive terms} \right) + \theta \left( \text{...} \right) + \text{constant}.

Solving \Delta_5(\theta_c) = 0 yields \theta_c \approx 0.25 for the nominal parameters. The derivation is available in the supplementary code.

